The city hung under a pall of grey, the roiling mass of cloud above and distant thunder promising a storm.  The streets were empty, with the exception of the few huddled figures going about their late-afternoon business.   From the hills to the east, the all-encompassing fog began to descend, making its way through the latticework of streets, tendrils of mist inquisitively groping at the forms of buildings and unlit street lamps.  The insistent wind pulls the fog towards the outskirts of the city, to a hill upon which a lone building stands, its stalwart and foreboding form the last bastion of civilization before the dark and untamed woods beyond.  From within this ancient, decrepit building can be heard the fevered sounds of the delirious, their unintelligible cacophonies echoing down the long, poorly lit halls.  At the end of one such hallway is a shadowed room, one of the numberless cells in this house of the insane.  Within, a frail figure lies in the corner of the room, curled upon the mold-infested floor.  The figure is that of an aged man, eyes bright with the intensity of madness, his long, unkempt beard and hair framing a face that had been hallowed by untold suffering.  Rocking back and forth in the darkness, the ancient man utters wordless litanies of hysteria, lost within his own twisted thoughts.  Each waking moment, every breath he takes brings unspeakable torment, for he is haunted by the self-created demons lurking in the lurid depths of his mind, a mind long without any vestiges of sanity.  He longs for the sweet release of sleep, but knows that he must suffer until the night, when he is administered his medication.  Until then, he waits, sequestered in the dark recesses of his mind, tortured by the misshapen, grotesquely howling denizens of his imagination.  Outside, rivulets of rainwater course languidly down the dirty glass of the window, framed by the sporadic flicker of lightning and shaken by the deep reverberations of thunder.  At last, its malevolent energy exhausted, the raging storm abates, and the clouds disperse, returning to their homes beyond the horizon, revealing the ivory crescent of the pure moon and the illimitable canvas of stars and distant galaxies beyond.  Within the asylum, a white-clad figure approaches the heavy door at the end of the hall, metal tray in hand.  Inside the cell, upon the moon-lit floor, the ancient man crawls towards the dark door.  With a rusty creaking, the door swings open, bathing the room in a dim glow.  The figure in white sets down the tray and eases the heavy door shut, securing the bolt on the other side.  Upon the tray rests a small porcelain cup, filled with a garish amber substance.  Trembling, the old man reaches for the crucible and the medicine within, the glowing golden elixir which would set him free.  Downing the mixture, the aged man coughs and hacks, almost choking, before catching his breath.  Ecstatic, the man begins to feel the effects of the elixir, the numbing, blissfully painless tranquility coursing throughout his body.  At last, he slips into unconsciousness, the silence of deep slumber enveloping him and his tortured visions utterly.
 

He wandered alone in the vast expanse of his mind, of the demons there was no sign.  He began his journey across the black wastelands of his dream, crossing through the horrendous valley of despair, luckily uninhabited by the demons of his waking nightmares, and at last arriving at the rolling plains of memory.  The crescent moon hangs over the foothills, basking the plains in a surreal glow.  The familiar sight of a small, homely cottage greeted the man as he strode across the silent fields of his ancient memories.  Opening the stained wooden door, he stepped inside.    The cottage was one-roomed, just as he had remembered it from his childhood long ago.  In the center was a small table, and two hand-carved wooden chairs neatly tucked under it.  He ignored the undisturbed furniture and turned to the far wall of the room.  Dominating this wall was large, intricately gilded mirror, fantastic images of long-forgotten tales and magnificent vistas adorning its golden frame.  Gazing into the shifting surface of the mirror, the old man beheld his ragged and time-worn body.  Touching the surface of the mirror, he felt energy begin to pour into him, racing from his fingertips into his arm and into his body.  Light poured forth from his aged form, and he felt his frail form being unmade.  At last, the transformation was complete, and he saw in the mirror opposite a figure, not the old and weakened man, but a remnant of past times, a healthy, vibrant young man, untouched by madness and the inexorable passage of time.  Smiling, he stepped outside, and regarded the night sky above him, stars dancing in ever-shifting patterns around the pale moon.  Closing his eyes, he began to rise into the air, currents of dream-wind carrying him upwards, towards the constellations.  He flew past the moon, past the winking lights of the dancing stars, until at last behind him, the dark hemisphere of his dream-world had disappeared completely.  Finally he broke through the obscuring mist of space and out into the night above the city, wings of crystalline filaments carrying him onwards.  He whirled above the sleeping city, letting himself be tossed about by the dream-energy of the thousands slumbering beneath him.  Reaching into his pocket, he drew forth a silver compass.  Eyeing the needle, he dived towards the city, racing past the rows of street lamps lining the empty streets.  At last he saw his destination, a small, shining golden dream-cloud suspended outside the window of a small apartment.  Upon the front of the cloud was a nondescript wooden door, and he reached for the silver knob.  The door was locked, and the man reached into his pocket and produced a magnificent silver key.  Sliding the key into the worn lock, he felt the tumblers fall away one by one.  The door opened before him, and he stepped through.  He found himself in a dark wood, the rotting trees interlaced with a creeping mist.  The air was stagnant, and the smell of sulphur was almost nauseating.  Suddenly, in the distance, a shrill scream pierced the stillness of the night.  He ran towards the sound, racing past fallen trees and decaying fauna.  He at last reached the source of the cry, a young boy cowering in a clearing.  He moved to console the distraught child, but from the woods leapt a massive beast, covered in long oily fur, its glowing, coal-like eyes burning in the darkness of the foreboding forest.  It strode forward, its maw glowing with row upon row of brilliantly sharp fangs, its massive paws adorned with wicked claws.  .  The beast faced the man, breath steaming with boundless hunger.  With a thought, the man created about himself a suit of golden armour, blindingly radiant in contrast to the sublime blackness of the beast.  Reaching once again into his pocket, the man withdrew his shining Vorpal blade, which grew into a great longsword, and turned to face the beast.  Its claws raked out in a wide arc, nearly catching the man, but he turned the blade up to block the great paws.  Vibrant sparks flew as the nightmarish claws of the monster clashed with the blade forged in the fires of pure imagination, both combatants expertly blocking and swiftly lashing out at the other, hoping to find an opening in the other’s defence.  At last the man saw his opportunity, and with a mighty thrust took the beast through the heart.  Roaring in agony, the great beast burst into flames, acrid smoke pouring forth from its eyes and mouth.  Soon, nothing was left of it except for a pile of smouldering ash and the fading echoes of its death throes.  Turning to the young boy, who gazed in amazement at this shining paladin, the man removed his crested golden helm and presented it to the child.  The boy eagerly accepted, and then ran off into the woods, now lush with greenery and lit by the warm glow of an evening sun.  The man felt the dream unravelling about him and cut himself loose from the strand tying him to the vision of the child, and found himself once more floating above the sleeping city.

1e10d84b3917ae58049be95b0071cf7f: It means they should be treated as meaningless strings, not as URLs They use the URL mechanism to provide global uniqueness The URL might point to a 404, which is fine though it shouldn't point to a non-existent domain because there's nothing to stop someone else picking the same non-existent domain You can parse microdata without needing to know the vocabulary (which is probably its main benefit over microformats) and I don't think there were compelling use cases for writing tools that process parsed data from vocabularies they know nothing about so it wasn't considered important to support that As far as I'm aware, you can define microdata vocabularies however you want and write machine-readable versions in whatever format you want and then code them into your microdata-using application and associate them with the item type identifier I think RDFa is designed to tie in with RDFish ways of defining vocabularies; microdata is designed to not care about that problem and merely to provide a tree of data that you can interpret however you want Dereferenced URL? 1e10d84b3917ae58049be95b0071cf7f: The URLs are compared as strings. The resembelence to URLs you use to access resources on the web is either a) useful or b) dangerously misleading, depending on your point of view It could be useful because the URL could point to some human-readable text explaining how to use the vocabulary It could be dangrously misleading because you might think that http://foo.example and http://foo.example/ were the same But they are not (since there is only string comparison) The reason that UAs must not automatically deference the URLs is that this constitutes a DDOS attack (see also: doctype URLs) 1e10d84b3917ae58049be95b0071cf7f: The danger is that a user might use some vocabulary that defines http://example.com and write http://example.com/ instead and be confused when noting works *nothing (or not notice, but have wasted their time) 1e10d84b3917ae58049be95b0071cf7f: And verbose. Per round of play, scores are submitted, the scores are computed, and a new page is generated with which turn you're in, the scores so far, etc. this lets you save the page when you decide to take a break, and resume the same game whenever you feel like it, but saving the page and then reopening it later. I'm considering turning it into a JS-only solution, but then saving the page to resume a game later becomes rather problematic, because it'll save the initial page, not the current state. s/but/by it's not the game. it's just the scoring. you play the game on a table top (shock horror! O_O) but the scoring is complicated, and a web page that tracks it is far easier than pen and paper. if someone wins a hand, you fill in what everyone has, then hit "score" and all the values are sent to the backend, the resulting who-pays-what-to-whom algorithm is run, and a new page is generated with fresh player sheets, and a new line in the "scores so far" list. (and a button that lets you examine why everyone got the score they got) doing that in javascript, rather than sending it to the backend, is fairly simple but doing it in such a way that you can just save the page, because it's getting late and you'll finish the game tomorrow, and then open it again the next day with the same state is hairy yeah but try sending data to the backend when you don't actually have internet access I'd like to move it all to just on-page js, while retaining the benefit of being able to resume the page with whatever browser you want to use. Encoding the history in the page is easy through DOM manipulation, but getting it saved seems impossible it's like browsers are suck in the era that "page I see" is equal to "the source I loaded" *Stuck currently? a reload just resubmits the data. that is hardly user friendly you ever play mahjong? "it takes hours" is not a joke. unless I'm playing with regular players, it's pretty common to end the evening not quite done, and just saving the page for resuming some next time. copy-pasting source code's not ideal. action="." because "." means "this location" and ".." means "one dir up" which parameters the latter. if you want to preserve parameters, add them to your form using "<input type='hidden' name='monkey' value='banana'>" you could write some JS to do this automatically based on window.location because arguments are single time things if I call "index.html?lol=rofl", then relative links are relative to my page. not to my page+args action takes any legal URL, and "." and ".." are legal URLs for "this dir" and "parent dir" which is why action="index.html" and action="./index.html" do the same thing a20e0580519fa0e9092d058a67627726, if you have a form that needs to preserve the arguments, simply use a bit of JS to extend your form, or modify the action. <form action="?I=maru"....> on a page "index.asp" will call index.asp?I=maru, for instance. So if you want to explicitly encode arguments that way, that's also fine come to think of it, action=?" might even work, although I never tried that O_o yes, when you want to break out of the default model for how HTML works, any recommendation I do involving "write some JS" is pretty serious =) no exactly, so break it with well written JS say I go to index.html?user=pomax and there's a relative link to "test.html" where should it go? ./test.html?user=pomax? I don't know, you're asking a question, I'm answering it, if you think that's a waste of time, something went wrong =) think of it this way: arguments are not HTML they are instructions to the server. which means that your server can do something with them, to generate content. that includes making sure that content that needs to further use them in links, has them right there. it's your responsibility. if you're using PHP or something to accept those arguments, then you get to write the code to inject them into the form that gets generates for that page. it's pretty simple that way you're missing the point. where do params *GO* if you have plain html content, they don't go anywhere, argument parsing is not part of HTML, it's part of "server-side handling" so that's where you make the magic happen. and that's how new technology is born. c5c4e16354e3a5e00f5dfc21328c2573, don't have an ipad (sadly =) but have you tried reducing to see if it does simply draw instructions like a plain canvas with some rect/paths? with some luck it'll turn out to be.
